New Book: The Human Bone Manual by Tim D. White & Pieter A. Folkens. Lets see if I can't ID what I've got now. I've got a lot of  really old (1800s) broken bone bits and nothing is fully articulated. FYI - I'm probably going to make vials of human bone dust. If anyone is interested please message me at my BoneLust Etsy shop or at FB. I can't sell human bone on Etsy but we can find a way around that. Anyway, this book is for archeologists, paleontologists & forensic anthropologists. Perfect for what I've got. Got great info & photos.

Girl_Ñés Bones Bear Signs of Cannibalism by Starving Virginia Colonists  Pictured: Human remains from the Jamestown colony site in Virginia bearing evidence of cannibalism. A facial reconstruction of a 14-year-old girl whose skull shows signs that her remains were used for food after her death and burial. A microscopic image shows sharp cuts to her jaw.  Archaeologists excavating a trash pit at the Jamestown colony site in Virginia have found the first physical evidence of cannibalism among the desperate population, corroborating written accounts left behind by witnesses. Cut marks on the skull and skeleton of a 14-year-old girl show that her flesh and brain were removed, presumably to be eaten by the starving colonists during the harsh winter of 1609.

Newest addition to my personal collection--a Burmese Tattoo Skull Bowl. These bowls were made of a real human skull, and were often prepared from the skulls of monks. They were decorated and used in the ritual of tattoo, which the Burmese people believed would give them power and protection in battle. The #Kelabit or also commonly called #Dayak are an indigenous people of the Sarawak/North Kalimantan highlands of #Borneo with a minority in the neighbouring state of Brunei. The elevation there is slightly over 1,200 meters. Because there are few roads and the area is largely inaccessible by river because of rapids, the highlands and the Kelabit are relatively untouched by modern western influences.  Elders are often talented carvers, carving earrings made from #hornbill #ivory and swords with handles made from human bones. The Kelabit was largely practiced #headhunting for #human #trophyskulls however this practice was seized in the late 80's or early 90's

Human skull with unique pathology for sale.  To start off with, this human skull has a prime example of temporal styloid process. This specimen also displays fused sagital and lamboid sutures. It is apparent from the rear view of this skull that the parietal and occipital bone/ protuberance are abnormally shaped.  As well, the occipital condyles are significantly off center and tilted which would cause quite the painful craniovertebral junction. The character in this skull speaks for itself! I received the raw quarters from a hunter uninterested in the meat.  I'll admit, this big guy did taste like he'd been into one too many trash barrels, but nothing a good stewing couldn't fix! Mid 19th Century Dayak Charms and Headhunter skull. Real Dayak trophy skulls are often split in two by means of a ceremonial tradition. The separation in itself is performed specifically at a certain point post death of neighboring victim following the adorned carving of the headhunter's process as he/she makes this victim part of their hunting record. One half is buried in the ground while the other half is kept. This particular skull is available for purchase.  Embody Museum _Ñ¢ Ethnographic Studies & Visual Arts. 19th century Asmat Ancestor skull _ÑÒNdambirkus_Ñ human skull, the lower jawbone tightly attached to the skull with a cord-like material, the eye-sockets are filled with beeswax, decorated with grey seeds of Job_Ñés-Tear Grass (Coix lacryma-jobi) and red seeds of the Crab_Ñés Eye Vine (Abrus precatorius). The nose is modelled with a blackish resin-like material, a piece of Cymbium shell was cut in the shape of a nose ornament. The head band is made with cord and Coix seeds and is decorated with tassels of feathers from the white cockatoo. Displayed with Asmat necklace composed of animal claws, fangs, paws, and textiles. This specific ancestor skull eliminates all suggestions that it was ever once a tourist piece like how many are often seen today. Aside from carbon dating bone, lab results from metallurgy tests reveal how the nose shell adornment was carved with no metal tools. In tourist pieces, metal carving sets such as a dremel are now used to shape the nose ornament.  Good Condition; just like normal household articles in Asmat culture human skulls were part of everyday life. The skull of a treasured ancestor was treated with outmost respect, it was dressed in a ceremonial manner and kept in a secure place. Sometimes it was attached to a cord and worn around the neck. The men used to carry the skulls around with them in order to keep in contact with the ancestors. When sleeping they used the ancestor skulls as a head rest. The skulls of enemies, called _ÑÒNdaokus_Ñ were kept in the mens house. They always show a hole in the side of the skull which was used to remove the brains which were later ingested. The lower jawbone was always separated from the skull and given to the women to wear as a necklace, which was regarded as the ultimate insult towards the enemy. Incredibly detailed and rare 18th century Tibetan necromancer's apron.  Human bone aprons are worn by Tantric deities and masters when they perform special rituals.  Originally from a Canadian museum, this piece has been in private hands for the last number of years, and due to the intricate carving detail, is believed to be mostly comprised of human bone (with the exception of the large deity pieces at the top). A very special piece that is near impossible to find at all, let alone in this condition!! 36mm Delrin Plug with human skullcap inlay.  Yes,This is real human bone.  It once was a living person. There is no need to get offended by it.  We live,we die,the bones stay.  Those where part of a medical skeleton for teaching purposes.  But since the 1950s they start replacing the real ones with composite replica.  The real ones get thrown away normally.  This is for giving them a third chance.  To make at least one person happy to look at.  #plug #plugs #humanbone #humanskull #handmadejewelry #bodyjewelry #handmade #jewelry

A vintage "3D anthropomorphic skull phantom" from my personal collection. These were produced by 3M and used for testing and calibrating x-ray machines. The model consists of a real human skull suspended in clear resin that is cast in the shape of a head. The resin was formulated to mimic how flesh appears on x-ray film. Each model had a slightly different facial structure because the resin was molded to match the individual skull it covered (in order to more accurately represent the thickness of the tissue that would have been present on that particular skull in real-life) Variations of this model are still manufactured today but are now made with a resin that is also compatible with CT and MRI machines. The modern models contain a replica skull, rather than a real one, and therefore all are identical.  #MedicalCollectable #AntiqueMedicalDevice #MedicalDevice #AntiqueMedical #AnatomicalModel #AnatomyModel #VintageAnatomicalModel #VintageAnatomyModel #SkullModel #HumanSkullModel #RealHumanSkull #HumanSkull #SkullCollecting #SkullCollection #BoneCollecting #ForensicReconstruction #DiagnosticImaging #FacialApproximation #MedicalTeachingDevice #AntiqueMedicalEquipment #XrayMachine #Oddity #Oddities #Curiosities #Wunderkammer #3MphantomSkull

Day 31 of #inktober (I decided to get out of my comfort zone again and draw a disfigured human skull for halloween) I really enjoyed doing a drawing a day this month. There were some days when I totally didn't want to draw anything but did. Some days I would put up a drawing and it would get hardly any likes but I would really like it. I would think it's my best one. Then there would be days when I put a drawing up and it would get a lot of likes but I wouldn't necessarily think it was even good. Idk. Art is weird. Circa 1400-1500s in Hradcany, Loretanske Square, this woman was discovered by archaeologists in 1934. She was thrown into her grave with her hands tied behind her back, to dislocate her shoulders and weighed down with rocks on her head and her feet, something that occurred from Pagan origins and was to prevent the deceased from returning to the living in the afterlife. Beside her is the body of a small child, buried at the same time. #skeleton #archaeology #bones #anthropology #customs #rituals #excavations #historylesson #beautiful #humanremains #skull #humanskull #museum #history #bohemia #czech #czechhistory #praha #prague #praha1 #prazskyhrad #castledistrict #eurowinter #eurotrip2015v2 #centraleurope #creepytour #creepypost

Possibly the most exciting thing for an anthropology nerd to find! This is the grave of the warrior, buried somewhere between 882-884 and carefully unearthed in 1928. What made him special is the fact that he was buried with STUFF. More specifically, he was buried with weapons and equipment to make fire. He was equipped to deal with whatever the afterlife threw at him! WWII Japanese Trophy Skull  Brought home by Dr. Dean B. Olewiler during his years of service during WWII.  Dean B. Olewiler, born in September of 1922 in Red Lion, Pennsylvania, son of Furnace Olewiler, a successful undertaker/funeral director in Red Lion. Dean Olewiler graduated from Jefferson Medical College in 1944 and immediately went into the military. Dr. Olewiler spent 2 years in the army, 9 months of that time were spent in the Asian Pacific Theater. During the war Dr. Olewiler was a lab technician as well as a part of the Graves Registration Service, in charge of going onto the field and removing the bodies of fellow soldiers. Dr. Olewiler brought home the skull of a Japanese soldier as a trophy and reminder of his time in Japan. In 1951 Dr. Olewiler and his wife Deborah left for London where Dr. Olewiler attended the London School of Tropical Medicines. From there he and his wife traveled to Nigeria to become Missionaries, he was the Director and Surgeon of Guinter Memorial Hospital. After their return in the 1960_Ñés, Dr. Olewiler went on to become the Medical Director of Alcoholic Rehabilitation at the Harrisburg State Hospital (the state mental institution of PA). Dr. Dean B. Olewiler died on June 14th 2008.  Though the skull was originally taken as a trophy, it was eventually labeled and used as a teaching tool. The skull exhibits multiple antemortem fractures as well as a splintered impact point at the occipital sinus which caused an outward fracture to the anterior of the occipital bone.

Tonight the Moon dreams with more indolence,  Like a lovely woman on a bed of cushions Who fondles with a light and listless hand  The contour of her breasts before falling asleep;  On the satiny back of the billowing clouds, Languishing, she lets herself fall into long swoons And casts her eyes over the white phantoms That rise in the azure like blossoming flowers.  When, in her lazy listlessness, She sometimes sheds a furtive tear upon this globe, A pious poet, enemy of sleep,  In the hollow of his hand catches this pale tear, With the iridescent reflections of opal, And hides it in his heart afar from the Sun's eyes.  Sadness of the Moon by C. Los Angeles County Sheriff_Ñés detectives recovered at least one apparent #humanskull and possibly others from a #Compton store where they were being used for Santeria religious ceremonies, officials said Friday.  Sheriff's homicide investigators said no foul play is suspected. But questions remain about how the skull was acquired. Eight other containers, still unexamined, were also recovered. "There is nothing sinister here," said Sheriff's Homicide Capt. Steve Katz. "The skull and possible eight other skulls in vessels were being used in #Santeria. The question is were the skeletal remains acquired appropriately." Katz said skeletal remains can be obtained legally under certain circumstances and that coroner's experts will determine whether the remains are human. He said one container was opened by investigators and they found a skull but the other eight said to contain skulls have yet to be examined. Sheriff's investigators went to the scene, a storefront advertising spiritual advice, in the 1500 block of North Long Beach Boulevard after reports of animal cruelty, Katz said.  On Friday, the parking lot was filled with television crews and curious residents.  Angie Garcia, 28, of Compton, said she used to attend Friday ceremonies at the location, called #OmiRelekun.  Inside, spiritual advisors dressed in white said they could communicate with the dead and cast out negative energy that clung to participants, she said.  Sometimes, the ritual called for the sacrifice of a live chicken, bird, or goat.  The mother of two said she was shocked to learn that authorities found what might be a human skull in the shop. "How scary," Garcia said. "I have kids around here. I know they worked with animals but not human skulls." The Santeria religion originated with the #Yoruba people of West Africa and came to the #Caribbean with blacks who had been sold into #slavery. During the 19th Century, it became enmeshed with elements of Catholicism.  The religious shop is tucked into a strip mall next to a store selling bottled water and another with blacked-out windows.  Metal bars covered the windows of Omi Relekun, which were arrows another symbols in white paint. #graffiti

I was incredibly lucky last night and picked up this beautiful specimen. My favorite anatomical preparatory maker, "Maison Tramond of Paris" created this mount in the mid 1800's. This one is signed and also has a plaque on the base by Tramond. All the veins, nerves, arteriesand eye are made of wax on a real human dissected skull. This is an incredible Inspiration to my own anatomical works and shall stay with me Til death. We choose instead to forego true happiness and betray one another for personal gain.  The powerful image of the corporeal skull represents our own mortality, while the juxtaposed 24 Karat gold leafing comments on man_Ñés immeasurable greed.

Ready for my new favorite project ever?! This here is a plug from the suture of a real human skull. It's been polished on the back, and mounted in a solid sterling silver, open back bezel. Like the perfect, odd little jewel it is! This is the first I've made, so it's a bit of a prototype, but I just love how it turned out. There will be more coming, from other parts of the skull, in other (the flower, and other sizes) bezels, with sterling chains. For those interested, this is from the remains of a 19th century European skull. It was nothing but a top skullcap when I got it, busted beyond all recognition. I would never destroy a perfectly good skull. I think this way it will get a little more "life" than it would as a chunk of bone on a shelf. #real #human #realskull #human #humanskull #bone #specimen #sutures #vultureculture #antiqueskull #deadstuff #mementomori #osteology #bonejewels #humanspecimen #humanjewelry #skulljewelry #realhumanskull #notonetsy #taboo #sterling #sutureline

This is a real Peruvian elongated skull! Dating back to 800-100BCE, this artifact of the Paracas culture is an incredible historical specimen!  In what is now the Ica Region of Peru, these peoples practiced cranial modification (cradle-boarding) on their infants to create abnormal skull development. This would typically be done between 1-6 months after birth when the human skull is most pliable.  It is believed that the altering of a child's head could be to denote higher status in a society or follow pseudoscientific beliefs that it would enhance the function of the brain.  We can ship this skull worldwide! The price has been significantly reduced due to the condition of the specimen. Authentic shanka altar piece, Tibet 1920-1950. The conch is decorated with semi-precious stones and tibetan silver. Engraved with tree-of-life dotwork, wich indicates temple use. The patina is outstanding!  I take offers or trade suggestions via DM.  A "tell" when buying Himalayan art: if the engraving is to precise, it's most likely a Chinese/Indonesian fake tourist piece. Look for edgecuts or dotworks because that's how authentic pieces where made. The tibetan silver is also ALWAYS solid. If you can see thru it somewhere and it's a redish (copper alloy) base it's a poorly made fake.  #skullforsale #vultureculture #skullsforsale #osteology #humanbone #humanskull #bonecollector #bones #realskull #wunderkammer #cabinetofcuriosities #skeleton #oddities #obscura #shanka #tibet #conch #artehimalyana #kapala

#fortheloveofgod is a #sculpture by artist #damienhirst in 2007. It consists of a #platinum cast of an 18th-century #humanskull #skull encrusted with 8,601 flawless #diamonds, including a pear-shaped #pinkdiamond located in the forehead that is known as the Skull Star Diamond. The skull's teeth are original, and were purchased by Hirst in #london. The artwork is a #momentomori or reminder of the mortality of the viewer. In 2007, art historian Rudi Fuchs, observed: 'The skull is out of this world, #celestial almost. It proclaims victory over decay. At the same time it represents death as something infinitely more relentless. Compared to the tearful sadness of a vanitas scene, the diamond skull is glory itself.'[1] Costing ë£14 million to produce, the work was placed on its inaugural display at the White Cube gallery in London in an exhibition Beyond belief with an asking price of ë£50 million. This makes it the highest price ever paid for a single work by a living artist.

The decision making process. Lay hundreds of pages of sketches on the table and pick the ones that speak to me at that particular moment, hook up the light board and begin the process of laying the concept down. Sketching my ideas on loose paper allows me to make mistakes and correct them prior to transferring the images used in a piece onto the final sheet of paper to allow for an undisturbed working surface. I've learned my lesson from excessive erasing on my heavyweight archival paper, ruining pieces because of surface degradation. I may not encounter these issues were I to work on a more forgiving surface but there is something about the effects that different paper weights and pressing processes can have on a piece (for better or worse) and the continuous learning process from trial and error that ensues  that has kept me aligned with the extraordinary league of paper and nothing else. #sketches #ideas #wip #worksinprogress #intestines #cats #catguts #guts #science #medical #medicaloddity #crosssection #skulls #humanskull #hands #portrait #teeth #bones #beardsley #skeleton #eyes #hair #drawings #art #artofinstagram #artist #insects #beetles

This evening for #wandwednesday we have a very special Relic Wand, a wand that is entangled in the very fabric of the origins of @USERNAME_HERE.  Bois de Rose and Bone, 11 & ë_ inch, Effervescent, with a core of Chimera Scale  This wand is called _ÑÒMagus_Ñ and was made many, many centuries ago by _ÑÒThe Wizard_Ñ the founder of Chimera Magic Supply, here is their story:  Although The Wizard had finally bested his greatest opponent in their final epic clash, the victory had not come easily. The Wizard lost his arm in the battle and though he did issue a devastating and fatal curse to the enemy, he did not see them die. This means the spell may not have been an instant kill and because of this he feared his nemesis had time to figure out how to come back to this world_Ñ_ in the next life. The Wizard was old and knew he was approaching his end of days. He could cast a spell and make himself live forever, but didn_Ñét want that. All The Wizard had ever wanted, in his entire life, was peace; and all he ever got to deal with was Chaos. He hoped in death he would find that peace for which he had always longed. So, knowing this, but also knowing he could not leave the world unprotected, he looked around the room and searched for an answer. As he peered across his chamber, he saw his recovered severed arm resting on his work table and like lighting, it hit him. The Wizard decided he would make a wand from his own bone and endow it with his spirit and energy. The Wizard_Ñés mind could live on in the wand, but his soul could finally be at peace. He found his rarest wood, a rosewood he discovered in a far off land; his strongest and rarest core, a full scale of the elusive Chimera; and his own Ulna bone. He worked through the night, one handed, but managed to create a wand he named _ÑÒMagus_Ñ. The Wizard cast an enchantment on the wand so once he died, Magus would choose his successor and that person would become _ÑÒThe Wizard_Ñ of the era. This way, every generation, from now until the end of time, would have The Wizard to protect them and Chimera Magic Supply would have a person to guide the shop into the next age.  #wand #humanbone #wizard #witch #harrypotter #woodworker #fantasy

New archeological skull ! This large male skull was exhumed at the former site of the Saint-Adelbert Abby at Egmond Binnen , in the Alkmaar region (North Holland). The Abby was founded in the 10th century and existed until 1573, when it was destroyed by Reformists during the Alkmaar siege.  The brick he sits on is a medieval brick known as a "kloostermop". These bricks were made by the monks which inhabited the Abby. This brick is original to the Saint-Adelbert Abby. The skull itself is at the very least 550 years old and could date back to as far as 1095 years.  He is marked with the excavation number NL22. I have to thank @USERNAME_HERE for the rare opportunity to own such an amazing piece of history.  Thanks for the good head buddy !!! My collection will forever be exquisitely historical. The staining seen here is the result of blood pooling post-mortem in a suicide by gunshot. This particular skull is interesting as the bullet was of a large caliber with low velocity. This is mostly associated with stray bullets versus suicide. It is unknown what circumstances caused the velocity to decrease. This skull was expertly prepped by the Charlotte, NC medical examiner and used in his pathology classes.  #anthropology #pathology #pathology #science #medicine #forensics #humanbone #humanskull #autopsy #brain #skull #death #wunderkammer #oddities #bone #cabinetofcuriosities

Lock Jaw:  Some people speak the words of illusion. I have even be guilty of such. Although I have come to a point in my life were I began to watch what I say to those around me not due to only fear but more of the fear that I would speak a lie. A lie that would trap me inside. I stay fighting with myself and only myself. Yesterday I came to clarity with a conversation that I began to have with a acutance. I began to speak to this person about keeping there side of the road clean and at that point it dawned on me that I myself need to take the same suggestion and that I have not been. Moments like this are a bright awaking and a sense of growth only those who experience moments like this will ever understand the beautiful clarity and gratitude for the other person presence. One of our more treasured pieces offered in the shop at the moment, a human Kapala. The human skull Kapala is a drinking vessel made of the skull cap of a fellow monk after a natural death. The use of a Kapala was described in less enlightened times as "the Hindoo communion" and the comparison is apt if a bit dated. The fellow monks drink wine from the skull cap, drinking left handed to imbibe the sinister qualities of the former occupant of the skull and drinking from the right to take in its qualities of goodness. Both in equal measure are important in the pursuit of transcendence, the pursuit of something bigger and more important than the self. I am personally too afraid to give any of this a try! #kapala #humankapala #skull #ritual #buddhist #buddhism #hindu #hinduism #spiritual #sacred #humanskull #antiques #skullcap #museum #collection #tibetanart #obscure #naturalhistory #tibet #art #reincarnation #transcendentalism #metalsmith #nevertold #hauntedgoods #feastkapala #ceremony

Torus mandibularis is a growth that is bony and nodular usually occurring along the lower jaw. It appears on inner surface of the jaw. When the bony growth occurs on the roof of the mouth or the palate, it is referred to as the patatinus but when it is presents in lower jaw, it is referred to as the torus mandibularis. The growth is usually attached to the jaw bone. This skull has the abnormality on both the Maxilla and mandible. Magus is quite possibly the most important relic wand we've ever encountered. Read on to learn of its integral role in Chimera Magic Supply.  Bois de Rose and Bone, 11 & ë_ inch, Effervescent, with a core of Chimera Scale  Magus was made many, many centuries ago by _ÑÒThe Wizard,_Ñ the founder of Chimera Magic Supply. Although The Wizard had finally bested his greatest opponent in their final epic clash, the victory had not come easily. The Wizard lost his arm in the battle and though he did issue a devastating and fatal curse, he did not see his enemy die. This means the spell may not have been an instant kill. Because of this he feared his nemesis had time to ensure a return to this world_Ñ_in the next life. The Wizard was old and knew he was approaching his end of days. He could cast a spell and make himself live forever, but didn_Ñét desire such burden. All The Wizard had ever wanted was peace, and all he ever dealt with was Chaos. He hoped in death he would find that peace for which he had always longed. But knowing he could not leave the world unprotected, he searched for a solution. As he peered across his chamber, he saw his recovered severed arm resting on his work table and like lighting, it hit him. The Wizard decided he would make a wand from his own bone and imbue it with his spirit and energy. The Wizard_Ñés mind could live on in the wand, but his soul could finally be at peace. He found his rarest wood and his strongest and rarest core. A rosewood he discovered in a far off land, and a full scale of the elusive Chimera. The final piece was his own ulna bone. He worked through the night, and managed to create a wand he named _ÑÒMagus._Ñ The Wizard cast an enchantment on the wand so once he died, Magus would choose his successor and that person would become _ÑÒThe Wizard_Ñ of the era. This way, every generation from now until the end of time would have The Wizard to protect them, and Chimera Magic Supply would have a person to guide the shop into the new era. . . . #wand #bone #humanbone #relic #wizard #witch #magic #harrypotter #fantasy #spell #spirit #woodworking #boisderose #chimera #ulna #cosplay #oddity #curiosities #etsy #etsyusa #etsyshop #chimeramagicsupply

Another human skull piece. This one is from a much more modern skull that was cleaned and peeped for a medical display. At some point it got smashed, and all that remained were pieces. So, I've cut an 18mm round cabochon from right at the broken suture line. You can see the jagged edge where the suture fused, as well as all the crazy veining where vessels etched holes and lines in the skull wall. I've encased it in resin and put it into this crown bezel. Will come on a matching 18" chain. $60 shipped with tracking in US. Comment SOLD to claim. Tribal artifacts from Papua New Guinea. The piece on the left has real human teeth, hair and mica eyes. Sometimes referred to as "replacement heads". These were created to pay homage to fallen ancestors. You can place you pre-order on the:  www.boristattoo.com  Price: 150 euros.  The reference photo collection is the third part of a longer, extensive, reference photo series including 600+ photos on flash drive.  The material is the continuation of the first two parts (vol. 1-2. which is also available again) and divided into four chapters:  1. Costume selection:  Fine art compositions with costumes, fixings and lights.  2. Flaming skull selection:  The first available, REALISTIC reference photo material of the traditional skull and flame principle tattoo motive.  Because of tribute reasons, the picturest have been made by using realistic skull replica.  3. Light painting selection:  By painting different patterns on the skull, Boris made special, unusual, revolutionary and up to now, never seen reference pictures.  4. Smoke selection: This is a new chapter of the reference photo collection. Misterious compositions with smoke and light. All is Vanity Charles Allan Gilbert  Charles Allan Gilbert drew this optical illusion picture in 1892, when he was 18 years old. After he sold it to Life Magazine and they reproduced it as a print, it became famous.  This is an ambiguous optical illusion, where we see more than one thing in the picture. If we view the overall image, we see a human skull. When we focus on the details of the picture, we see a woman looking in her vanity mirror.  The phrase "All is vanity" comes from the book of Ecclesiastes in the Christian Bible. It refers to the vanity and pride of man. In art vanity has long been represented as a woman preoccupied with her beauty. And art that contains a human skull as a focal point is called a memento mori (Latin for "remember you will die"), a work that reminds people of their mortality.  If we look at a close-up, cropped image of "All is Vanity", we don't see the skull, we just see details of a woman sitting at her dressing table. But if we expand our view, even without seeing the entire image, once we know we're going to see a skull, we can't help but see it. #opticalillusion #art #drawing #print #humanskull #woman #vanity #mirror #allisvanity #beauty #mementomori #morality

Stunning antique medical fracture/brain surgery human skull for sale. This skull is of an individual who survived major cranial surgery. You can see where a large section  had been dissected and over a period of time the bone started to fuse back together. This subject was quite old, you can see the teeth are mostly absent and the bone has receded and morphed the skull. Must have been a bizarre looking fellow. Pathological skulls are about the most difficult to find! Some close ups of the super cool and super interesting pathology and work done on this skull. Check out that wisdom tooth growing in sideways in the top left two shots! Then the simulated broken jaw with hardware to stabilize it. The tops of the mandible that have simulated breaks to show how healing would appear. This skull has a super pronounced sagittal suture, (the line where the frontal and parietal bones fuse forming a Y shaped line) the fact it is so open makes me wonder if this skull was from an adolescent and the bones hadn't fused all the way. Looking at the underside of the skull you can see the replacement palate and how the maxilla was cut to fit this skulls features. #skull #humanskull #humanbones #skulls #osteology #oddity #medical #medicalspecimen #surgery #surgical #iheartautopsy #oddmonton #facialreconstruction

Spent the morning looking through some of my photos from Soutn America. When I photographed this skull I was initially suspicious, because it demonstrates a level of skull binding and subsequent distortion that's so severe I thought it might be a fraud. But I really examined it and as far as I can tell it's completely real. What a skull! And not only that, it's not in a museum proper, it's in a glass display case at a public swimming pool, near Chivay in Colca Canyon. So basically, America has a lot to learn here. How many public swimming pools have skulls on display at all, much less like this? Don't ever laugh as a hearse goes by, for you may be the next to die. They wrap you up in a big white sheet, from your head down to your feet. And all goes well for about a week, then your coffin starts to leak. And the worms crawl in the worms crawl out, the worms play pinochle on your snout. They eat your eyes they eat your nose. They eat the jelly between your toes. A big green worm with rolling eyes, crawls in your stomach and out your eyes. Your stomach turns a slimy green, and puss comes out like whipping cream. You spread it in a slice of bread, and that's what you eat when you are dead. And the worms crawl out the worms crawl in. The worms that crawl in are lean and thin. The ones that crawl out are fat and stout. Your eyes fall in and your hair falls out. Your brain comes tumbling down your snout. And the worms crawl in, the worms crawl out. They crawl all over your dirty snout. Your chest caves in and your eyes pop out, your brain turns to sauerkraut. They invite their friends, and their friends too. They all come down to chew on you. And this is what it is to die, I hope you had a nice goodbye. Did you ever think as a hearse goes by, that you might be the next to die? And your eyes fall out and your teeth decay, and that is the end of the perfect day. Antique medical preparation of a dissected Temporal bone from a human skull. Comes mounted on its original stand. Circa 1920, USA. This piece is cut in the middle so the bones can be examined as well as the cross section and inner auditory ossicles. There is is small hook that holds the two bones together. There is a hand-written makers mark that reads "Clay Adams Co, Inc New York". The nerves and arteries are represented in blue and red paint. Overall in perfect condition. This piece is being sold for medical purposes and comes with its original articulated hardware. $350. This process is often called "exploding" a skull, but is more formally known as a "Beauchene skull" after 18th century french anatomist Claude Beauchene who was renowned for creations such as these, used for medical reference. This is a truly unique specimen.

I always find something that I've never seen before when I visit the American Museum of Natural History.  The museum is home to millions of artifacts, so I take comfort in that fact that I have only seen a fraction of the collection.  Saturday I noticed this African poison flask decorated with human jaw bones.  It quickly became my new favorite, replacing a mummified Peruvian head as my favorite.  Something about this poison flask just draws me in, it's both terrifying and mesmerizing for reasons that somehow escape me. #americanmuseumofnaturalhistory #poisonflask #humanbone #bone #african #artifact #anthropology #museum #staycurious #naturalhistory #culturalhistory

This Terrifying Creature Evolved Specifically To Hunt Humansë_ê__êô_  There once were these big cats that considered humans as their number one prey. These felines were called Dinofelis, and they had huge daggers for teeth. These dagger-like teeth could easily puncture a human skull. The Dinofelis was deadly to humans and were guarded against. It is speculated that the reason humans built spears was specifically to defeat the Dinofelis. New piece for the Oddmonton personal collection..... An antique Tibetan damaru made from 2 human skull caps, and what is believed to be human skin for the drum skins.  This piece was originally purchased from a tourist in Tibet approximately 16 years ago, and has been in a personal collection ever since.  Damarus are used as instruments in Buddhist tantric practices, and are traditionally made using the skull caps of 2 monks.  This piece is estimated to be approximately 100 years old. Human Bone Rings: In 2006 there was an article in BBC News about The Biojewellery project, a joint effort between designers Mr Kerridge and Nikki Stott from the Royal College of Art in London, and Dr Ian Thompson, a bioengineer from Kings College London. Five couples were selected out of 180 volunteers to have bone cells (osteoblasts) extracted from their wisdom teeth at Guys Hospital, London, and made into rings which the couples could exchange. (Wisdom teeth were used rather than bone biopsies as it was thought to be a safer, less-invasive procedure.) The process took 6-10 weeks and was originally a way to engage the public with bio-engineering as well as eventually grow larger, complete bones for people who need them. As an ex autopsy technician, I remember that the deceased who kindly donated bone and skin had a longer window than other organ donors - it was up until about 72 hours before bone and skin couldn't be harvested anymore (with eyes it's more like 24). It got me thinking: couldn't this be a new form of memento mori jewellery? After death, after autopsy even, osteoblasts could be harvested to make jewellery... #humanremains #remains2beseen #humanbone #bonering #mementomori

Skull' bij Vincent van Gogh, 1887/1888.  Vincent commited suicide by shooting himself in the chest at the age of 37. Over 150 psychiatrists have attempted to diagnose the root of his mental problems. Among the suggestions are schizophrenia, bipolar disorder, syphilis, poisoning from swallowed paints, temporal lobe epilepsy, and acute intermittent porphyria. Any of these could have been the culprit, and could have been aggravated by malnutrition, overwork, insomnia, and consumption of alcohol, especially absinthe. #vincent #vangogh #vincentvangogh #dutchartist #painting #skullpainting #skull #death #suicide #humanskull #postimpressionism #artist #mentalillness #schizophrenia #bipolar #acourseindying

When you are walking through the choeung ek killing fields and start the discovery of a human skull in the ground. ê__êôµApparently this is normal as during rainy season, the rain washes away the soil and brings the human bones closer to the surface. Naga Tribe Head-Taking Basket. Northeast India. Like many "Headhunters", the Naga did not run around #beheading anyone that was not part of their kin nor did they kill rambunctiously during tribal warfare. This notion is actually quite inaccurate. Certain Naga warriors who were also headhunters actually acted similarly as Police. Within the family kin or not, various degrees of punishment were permitted depending on severity of crime. Both social and politics were structured as a foundation when determining punishment. This bizarre tribal human skull was decorated by the Asmat peoples of New Guinea!  While they are famous for their headhunting, this particular item is not a trophy skull. It is an "Ancestor Skull" - traditionally the skull of a deceased relative, exhumed in an effort to strengthen their spiritual connection and call forth guidance and protection.  This particular piece is a vintage trade item and was not looted from these aboriginal peoples.  This specimen can be shipped worldwide! Buy it now on www.SkullStore.ca! An important aspect to me while photographing is to be one with the people that I_Ñém photographing._Ñ says photographer Trupal Pandya about his project The Head Hunters.  The Head Hunters is a very interesting documentary portrait project that tries to spotlight a people and a culture that is mostly going away. For some of this project, it was important to Trupal to really emphasize the subjects by using a white backdrop. I came upon this crazy archaeological photo and had to share it! This is a soldier, with his sword still in its sheath, that was killed by the pyroclastic flow of Mount Vesuvius erupting in 79AD. "The same heat that carbonized objects reduced people to skeletons. This man, found on the ancient shore of Herculaneum, was wearing a belt of silver and bronze plaques and carrying a long sword and stabbing dagger. He is thought to be a soldier. The volcanic surge hurled him down with huge force, breaking his bones.  His blackened skeleton shows death was instantaneous. Exposed to the full force and high temperature of the surge, his body was burnt to the bone in seconds."

Female Geriatric Human Skull. This skull is very unique in that it appears to be missing the Sagittal suture along the back of the cranium. This condition is known as Craniosynostosis, and is caused by a premature fusing of the the Sagittal suture before the brain has fully developed. As a result there is a slight bump at the top of the cranium although it seems this person lived a full life without any serious life threatening consequences. Beautiful patina to this specimen. This is the skeleton of soldier killed during the Thirty Year War in the battle of LÕ_tzen, Germany on November 16, 1632.  In this particular battle a Protestant army lead by Sweden's King Gustav II Adolf clashed with the Catholic Habsburg imperial army under the command of Albrecht von Wallenstein. On that fateful, foggy, day 20,000 soldiers battled to the death with between 6,000 and 9,000 meeting their grizzly end - including King Gustav.  This unknown soldier was found buried in a mass grave. Many mysteries (and bodies) likely still lay unearthed at this old battleground. The ability to excavate has been severely limited as the site is now host to a supermarket, nursing home and a small garden space.

Proud new owner of this brutal and beautiful piece. . 'For the warriors of the wasteland, @USERNAME_HERE in collaboration with @USERNAME_HERE presents the Outlaw Rosary, limited to 13 pieces. . Fashioned from cow-bone beads, human bone, wolf teeth and 92.5 silver.  Each run of beads has been numerically chosen for its corresponding runic principle, brought together by a human bone centerpiece and a sterling silver black sun, hand-made by one of our collaborators. . From "P" of Death Ritual, a short excerpt from the hand-numbered descriptor card that will ship with each order: . "The wolf has forever lived in the mind and myth of man as a symbol of wildness, strength, fury and freedom. Placed as dividers, its teeth remind the wearer that the true outlaw exists on the Other Side...he is in the woods, always, in his heart. . The connecting bead of human bone is a memento mori of sorts. This life is to be lived to the hilt, and at the sudden, savage end- our Father, Death, awaits us all. . The Black Sun is a light on the path traversed by the Outlaw King, and a destroying weapon of awful power to those who would obstruct his way. Like the world ending destructive power of Rudra, it is the holy black sun's spiritual might that is evoked physically in the berserk rage, the blitzkrieg, the atomic bomb.  Traversing the razor's edge between reckless self-destruction and enlightened freedom of action, he who burns a fiery road to freedom must ride forever watchful, forever lawless, forever :R:ising." . :: Image from @USERNAME_HERE :: . #deathritual #shownomercy #wolf #wolfbone #humanbone #rosary #blacksun #outlaw #kingdeath #death #power #rudra #berserkr #mementomori #13 #92 #ritual #altar #wolfteeth #cowbone #silver #occult

There is alot of new fans on the page lately so i thought i would cover some basics of what i do. I do what i do for me the fact that other people dig it is just an added bonus. I just make stuff cos i have to sometimes I'll make 10 pieces in a week other times I'll go months without creating but i am always collecting and processing bones and subject matter for when the scratching in my head from the creatures inside gets to loud and the urge to create takes hold. I take great pride that every subject i work on is ethically sourced. No animal is harmed for my art. Most is road kill alot is hunting waste and some is donated from fans. My artwork is not for the faint of heart and some will argue its just plain shocking. The fans who love it simply cant get enough of it and those who hate it down right despise it. To me both of these are the greatest compliments i can recieve as an artist.Skullduggery by Clay#skullduggerybyclay #skullcollector #skull #humanskull #cabinetofcuriosities #colletor #boneartist  #bones #bonesmith #maceration #bonesdontgrowonthebonetree #iplaywithdeadthings #soyouwanttobeabonecollector #sorrytohearyourpetdiedcanihaveit

But I did keep her owner's manual and now I'm using it as collage fodder one page at a time.

Sometimes specimens like this are my favourite to repair. This is a section showing Bony Ankylosis (two bones fused together) of the right tibia and ankle of a 22 year old male. The thing is, it dates from 1887, the fluid it's in (probably alcohol from that date) has never been changed and yet you can see how clear it is! It means all I need to do is clean it, give it a new label and hand paint the top and suddenly it looks as good as new. Skull drawing. Alberto Giacometti 1901\u201366 Swiss sculptor and painter; son of the impressionist painter Giovannia Giacometti; b. Stampa. He settled in Paris in 1922 studying with Bourdelle and becoming associated first with the cubists and then the surrealists. His Slaughtered Woman (1932; Mus. of Modern Art New York City) for example is a violent surrealist work. Giacometti abandoned surrealist images in 1935. In the 1930s and thereafter he created highly original sculptures of elongated emaciated human figures usually in bronze. He also made open cagelike structures that were equally powerful. #modernart #skull #humanskull #drawing #human #anatomy #doctorknows

Skull of a young adolescent who died from hydrocephalus 19th century. Hydrocephalus (from Greek hydro- meaning \water\" and kephalos meaning \"head\") is a medical condition in which there is an abnormal accumulation of cerebrospinal fluid in the brain. This causes increased intracranial pressure inside the skull and may cause progressive enlargement of the head if it occurs in childhood potentially causing convulsion tunnel vision and mental disability. It was once informally called \u201cwater on the brain\u201d and was almost always fatal in earlier periods. Gorgeous photo by Joakim Blockstrom. This remarkable specimen is housed at the Hunterian Collection at the Royal College of Surgeons in London which is open & free to the public. I highly recommend you visit the museum if you ever find yourself in the area. #darkhistory #histmed #medicalhistory #medicalhistory #skulls #humanskull #humananatomy #museumobject #anatomy #specimen #hydrocephalus #19thcentury #victorian #darkobject #followme"

This anatomical specimen is the oldest known in Europe. The gruesome specimen now in a private collection consists of a human head and shoulders with the top of the skull and brain removed. Rodent nibbles and insect larvae trails mar the face. The arteries are filled with a red \metal wax\" compound that helped preserve the body. The preparation of the specimen was surprisingly advanced. Radiocarbon dating puts the age of the body between A.D. 1200 and A.D.1280 an era once considered part of Europe's anti-scientific \"Dark Ages.\u201d For more on this specimen see article on Live Science (link in comments). Carved from a single piece of ivory this model of a human skull sits upon crossbones. Not much is known about this model but it probably dates from the 19th century and served as a memento mori reminder of death. The skull was the symbol of death from the 16th century onwards. The object was part of the private collection of Dr Noel Hamonic (d.1928) but is now part of the Wellcome Collection in London. #mementomori #humanskull #darkobject #darkhistory #victorianswag #deathsalon #curios #ivory #followme

This is my photograph from my visit to Sedlec Ossuary just outside Prague a couple of years ago. The reason I_Ñém posting today is The Express has a new article about it explaining the reasons behind some of the dÕ©cor. Founded in the 13th century, the church's graveyard completely filled up with more than 30,000 bodies by the end of the 1400s. Soldiers who met untimely deaths and victims of the plague were many among them. To make room for more, the remains were exhumed and moved to the underground church where bones piled up in pyramid formations over the years. It wasn_Ñét until 1870 when a noble family stepped in that the bones became decorations. Artist Frantisek Rint began the laborious task of covering the surfaces of the holy site in bones. Today more than 40,000 bleached skeletal remains can be seen throughout, where bones hang from the ceiling, line the walls and even form chalices. The centrepiece is a chandelier with every bone in the human body dangling from it and is believed to represent the seven-headed beast from the Book of Revelation in the Bible. #humanremains #humanbone #remains2beseen #bones #bonechurch #ossuary #sedlec #prague #skeleton #skull #skeletons #skulls #graves #graveyard #cemetery #beinhaus #bonehouse

*One of Two* This 16th/17th century skull is engraved with what is known as a Sator Square or Quader (cuboid). The square\u00a0contains a Latin\u00a0palindrome\u00a0featuring the words\u00a0SATOR AREPO TENET OPERA ROTAS\u00a0written in such a formation that they can be read top-to-bottom bottom-to-top left-to-right and right-to-left. One theory is that the words roughly translate as \u201cthe farmer uses his plough as his form of work.\u201d Although not a very impressive sentence it is grammatical: it can be read up down backwards and forwards. When written the opposite way (i.e. with ROTAS at the top) it\u2019s known as a Rotas Square. It\u2019s not just engraved into human remains! The earliest dateable Sator Square was found in the ruins of\u00a0Pompeii which was buried in the ash of\u00a0Mount Vesuvius\u00a0in 79 AD. Examples may be found carved on stone tablets or pressed into clay worldwide: UK Italy France Portugal and more.It does have some occult significance which I\u2019ll explain in the next post. (If you like it you can buy a pendant from @USERNAME_HERE and amazing Venetian jewellers Codognato have recreated it as a ring too. You can see it in one of my tweets: https://goo.gl/lKOv7i#humanremains #remains2beseen #skull #skulls #humanskull #satorskull #satorsquare #rotassquare #palindrome #occult #anatomy #osteology #killstar #codognato

*Two of Two* The\u00a0Sator or Rotas Square\u00a0is a four-times palindrome and some people have attributed\u00a0magical properties\u00a0to it considering it one of the\u00a0broadest magical formulas in the\u00a0Western world. An article about this square from\u00a0The Saint Louis Medical and Surgical Journal\u00a0vol. 76 reports that palindromes were viewed as being immune to tampering by the\u00a0devil who would become confused by the repetition of the letters and hence their popularity in magical use. This item therefore may have been used in necromancy: magic which requires deceased body parts. Necromancy obviously has quite negative connotations but perhaps this was used for good. It has reportedly been used in\u00a0folk magic\u00a0for various purposes including putting out fires removing jinxes and fevers\u00a0to protect cattle from witchcraft\u00a0and against fatigue when traveling.\u00a0It is sometimes claimed it must be written upon a certain material or else with a certain type of ink to achieve its magical effect and perhaps this particular spell insisted it was carved onto a skull for more potency. I will hopefully be doing a lecture on Necromancy in London this autumn!#humanremains #remains2beseen #skull #skulls #humanskull #satorskull #satorsquare #rotassquare #palindrome #occult #anatomy #osteology #necromancy #folkmagic

Skull from the Fontanelle Cemetery in Naples. I got an email from a local friend telling me the city might be closing this place again. Whether the Fontanelle will be open or closed has been an ongoing drama in Naples for a couple decades with no apparent rhyme or reason to the pattern of closures. But basically if you haven't been and you're in Italy--go visit in case it gets shut down again. The Fontanelle itself is a cave system filled with bones a remnant of the days when the city used to toss human remains into subterranean storage as a natural charnel house. The living eventually came down and started adopting and enshrining certain skulls as paranormal helpers and confidants. The Fontanelle is huge; it has the best skulls shrines folklore and ghost stories in Europe. True story . . . the first time I visited was when I was researching my book Empire of Death. It was closed back in those days but I was allowed to enter with a custodian from the city. With us was a very old lady who used to tend a skull here named Pasquale during her youth. She wanted to talk to him again. When we entered the cave she said she heard him calling to her and fixed on a spot. We helped her search but we did not find Pasquale and she went home disappointed. Months later I received a message from the custodian. He had excavated more of the rubble and he had found that there was a board covered over by dirt where the lady had been standing. When he pulled up the board he found several more skulls. One of them was in a cracked shrine with the name Pasquale on it. All Is Vanity'\u00a0(1892) by C. Allan Gilbert - a prominent American\u00a0illustrator. He is especially remembered for this widely published drawing (a\u00a0memento mori\u00a0or\u00a0vanitas). The drawing employs a double image (or\u00a0visual pun) in which the scene of a woman admiring herself in a mirror when viewed from a distance appears to be a human skull. The title is also a pun as this type of dressing-table is also known as a vanity. The phrase \All is vanity\" comes from\u00a0Ecclesiastes\u00a01:2 (Vanity of vanities saith the Preacher vanity of vanities; all is vanity.)\u00a0It refers to the vanity and pride of man. In art vanity has long been represented as a woman preoccupied with her beauty. And art that contains a human skull as a focal point is called a memento mori (Latin for \"remember you will die\") a work that reminds people of their mortality.*image cropped & edited*#pride #vanity #prideandvanity #allisvanity #Ecclesiastes #mementomori #death #skull #humanskull #doubleimage #visualpun #youwilldie #sardonic #humour #humor ;)"

Human skull inscribed for phrenological charts 19th century. One half accords with Gall's theories the other Spurzheim\u2019s theories. Phrenologists believed that the shape and size of various areas of the brain (and therefore the overlying skull) determined personality. Phrenological heads were used as reference guides for people carrying out consultations. Although phrenology became popular with large numbers of people in the 1800s it soon became controversial within medical circles and was eventually dismissed by the medical profession as quackery. However phrenology was still studied in the United Kingdom until 1967 when the British Phrenological Society finally closed. #phrenology #humanskull #skulls #victorianscience #quakery #histmed #medicalhistorian #histsci #followme

Photo I took a few years back in a storage area of the Palermo Catacombs where pieces that have fallen off miscellaneous bodies and can't be reattached are hidden. In the late 19th century a man named Giacomo came to this room and stole one of the skulls and spent the next month ritually defecating on it. Why would he do such a weird/terrible thing? Well it's a long story but I just bought a ticket to Houston and I'm going to explain it there in a talk for @USERNAME_HERE on September 16. I'm finally doing a talk in Texas. One of my favorites of the ostensible martyr skeletons from the Roman catacombs is St Getreu. After I photographed him I went back to visit a couple times; I love how the silk cloth veils his skull without obscuring it and the way it's bordered in jewels and embroiery. But what I did not know about him until today when I had a chance to talk to an old priest from his church was that in the 1960s his skull was stolen. A woman came in and thinking no one was looking pulled his skull loose shoved it under her skirt and attempted to walk out. The church staff pursued her and when she tried to run the skull fell out from between her legs. I've always believed the 1960s must have been a magic time on so many levels. #whatsbetweenyourlegs #skull #humanskull #catacombsaints #heavenlybodies #mementomori

Alaskan Inuit (Eskimo) Skull showing the effects of syphilis c.1910. The severe pitting in this skull is the direct result of tertiary (last stage) syphilis a bacterial infection often transmitted through sexual contact - though infected mothers can pass it onto children in what is known as congenital syphilis. Sometimes referred to as \Cupid's Disease\" syphilis was fatal before the discovery of #penicillin in 1928. In the final stage the disease attacks a person's skeletal structure as well as the brain and nervous system which often manifests itself in a form of madness. This skull is from the Wellcome Collection in London. #syphilis #histmed #medicalhistory #humanskull #skulls #humanremains #antiobiotics #medschoollife #followme"

Death's-head Hawkmothgenus: #Acherontia #vuurtoreneiland #nearamsterdam These #moths are easily distinguishable by the vaguely #humanskull-shaped pattern of markings on the #thorax and have several unusual features. All three species have the ability to emit a loud #squeak if #irritated. The #sound is produced by expelling air from the pharynx often accompanied by #flashing of the brightly colored abdomen in a further attempt to deter #predators. All three species are commonly observed raiding #beehives of different species of honey bee for honey; A. atropos only attacks colonies of the well-known Western honey bee Apis mellifera. They can move about in hives without being disturbed because they mimic the scent of the bees.[1] (SourceWikipedia)

Exit wound from a gunshot to the head 18th century. This is a photo I took of a skull from a young man who committed suicide in the 1780s. It comes from the crypt of St. Bride\u2019s Church in London. Though attitudes towards suicide began to shift during the Enlightenment (from explanations of \u201csin\u201d to \u201cinsanity\u2019) the act was still taboo at the time of this young man\u2019s death. Those who committed suicide were often forbidden from being buried in consecrated ground. So how did he end up buried in the crypt of a church? His family disguised his suicide in his death certificate which read: \u201cdropped dead suddenly.\u201d These particular skeletal remains along with many others from the Crypt of St. Bride\u2019s Church are currently being studied by osteoarchaeologists. #archaeologylife #humanremains #humanskull #skulls #darkhistory #breakingtaboos #crypts #followme

#Repost @USERNAME_HERE\u30fb\u30fb\u30fbPhoto I took a few years back in a storage area of the Palermo Catacombs where pieces that have fallen off miscellaneous bodies and can't be reattached are hidden. In the late 19th century a man named Giacomo came to this room and stole one of the skulls and spent the next month ritually defecating on it. Why would he do such a weird/terrible thing? Well it's a long story but I just bought a ticket to Houston and I'm going to explain it there in a talk for @USERNAME_HERE on September 16. I'm finally doing a talk in Texas. The severed head of Sir Simon Sudbury hacked off during the Peasants\u2019 Revolt in 1381. The Revolt had various causes including the socio-economic and political tensions generated by the Black Death in the 1340s the high taxes resulting from the conflict with France during the Hundred Years' War and instability within the local leadership of London. Sudbury was Archbishop of Canterbury and Lord Chancellor of England at the time of his death. In January 1380 a group of insurgent peasants attacked and damaged the Archbishop's property at Canterbury and Lambeth; then rushing into the Tower of London they seized the Archbishop himself. So unpopular was Sudbury because of his introduction of a third poll tax that guards simply allowed the rebels through the gates. Sudbury was eventually dragged to Tower Hill where he was beheaded after eight blows to his neck. His body was buried in Canterbury Cathedral though his head (after being taken down from London Bridge) is still kept at the church of St Gregory at Sudbury in Suffolk which Sudbury had partly rebuilt. #darkhistory #toweroflondon #executions #severedhead #humanskull #skulls #darkages #followme

Bought a plane ticket to Bolivia. I'll be doen there in November for the Fiesta de las Natitas the annual skull festival. I've been going for the past decade. This photo is from the first year I went but it hasn't changed much. It's still the best thing in the world. True story: two years ago I asked a lady if I could photograph her skull and she said yes. I took some pictures and was leaving when another guy asked to photograph it. She said no which surprised him and me also. The guy asked \how come he can photograph it and not me?\" She said \"he comes every year and he makes my skull look good. You I don't know.\" That's when I knew I had beem accepted as part of the gang. #bolivia #lapaz #natita #calavera #skull #humanskull"

This is a real human skull that has been carved with a range of occult imagery centered around a depiction of Baphomet!Baphomet was the idol that the Knights Templar were accused of worshipping during the Inquisition in the early 14th century and has since become a part of multiple pagan occult and mystical traditions. In 1856 Eliphas Levi created the image of a \Sabbatic Goat\" that has come to represent Baphomet. The elements of this symbology represent the \"sum total of the universe\" (including the balance of good and evil). This is a carving by European artist Dolen Carag and the specimen can be shipped worldwide anywhere the ownership of human osteology is legal. Buy it now on www.SkullStore.ca or email BuySkulls@USERNAME_HERE.com to arrange payment plans!"

Close-up of human skull painted with phrenological charts 19th century. In the 1800s phrenology became popular with large numbers of people but soon became controversial within medical circles. Phrenologists believed that the shape and size of various areas of the brain (and therefore the overlying skull) determined personality. Phrenologists also disagreed among themselves as is demonstrated by this skull. One half of the head shows the system according to Franz Joseph Gall (1758 \u20131828) a German physician and founder of phrenology and the other half shows the system favoured by his colleague Johann Gaspar Spurzheim (1776-1832). The labels are written in French. This skull is part of the Wellcome Collection in London which is free to visit. #humanremains #humanskull #phrenology #histmed #medicalhistorian #darkhistory #museumobject #histsci #skulls #skeleton #followme

A skeleton from the \u201cOur Buried Bones\u201d exhibition at the Hunterian Medical Museum in Glasgow. This special exhibition unearths the stories behind four skeletons from the Museum of London\u2019s 20000-strong collection and four from burial grounds across Scotland. On display together for the first time they reveal rich and eventful life stories with individuals coming from diverse locations and periods of time from the plague pits of urban London to the beaches of South Uist. Using the latest scientific methods careful analysis by experts has provided insights into the health and history of each individual bringing to life stories that have long been hidden beneath the ground. Each skeleton exhibits pathologies that expose the multiple challenges of life in the past from fractures and trauma cancer and the effects of syphilis to rickets arthritis and tooth decay. The exhibition is open with free entry until 8 January 2017 and will then travel on to Bristol and Leeds. Photo Credit: Callum Bennetts. #museumexhibition #humanremains #skeleton #humanskull #archeologylife #histmed #medicalhistorian #archeologist #excavations #followme

Medieval skeleton for sale!! This skeleton belonged to a medieval Dominican Frier Pastor  from roughly 1250AD! This holy man died only ~35 years after the founding of the Dominican Order (a sect of the Catholic Church). This individual would have been a member of the initial spread of their sect into Belgium but their order would later grow into one of the most influential religious groups in the Middle Ages.This archaeological skeleton comes with dig site reports from the excavation of the old church grounds and the row of burials he would have come out of. The exact ID is unknown but it was in the pastor burial grounds and originally purchased from the archaeologist who made the excavation.The bone placement in the photographs is not intended to be anatomically perfect it is simply indicative of the completeness of the specimen.We can ship this rare specimen worldwide anywhere the ownership of human osteology is legal! For more photos and to buy it now visit www.SkullStore.ca!

My most prized osteological possession - maybe even just my most prized thing I own - a lepers skull. The history behind this skull is amazing. Brought back from a leper colony by a doctor in the early 1900s this ladys remains had been disposed of on a bonfire in front of a temple with many others. The doctor took her skeleton from the pyre and brought her to england to study. When the doctor died it was passed down through his family the rest of the skeleton crumbling away throughout the years. The skull was given to me by the doctors great grand daughter. The skull has scorch marks on the back of her head and is incredibly brittle. #osteology #leper #skull #humanskull #pyre #temple #lepercolony #bones #skeleton #morbidhistory #curios #oddity #medicalantique

Peking Man (Chinese: Îë„__åëË___; pinyin: BÛ_ijÛ‚ng Yuíçnrí©n), Homo erectus pekinensis (formerly known by the junior synonym Sinanthropus pekinensis), is an example of Homo erectus. Discovered in 1923äóñ27 during excavations at Zhoukoudian (Chou K'ou-tien) near Beijing (written "Peking" before the adoption of the Pinyin romanization system), China, in 2009 this group of fossil specimens dated from roughly 750,000 years ago, and a new 26Al/10Be dating suggests they are in the range of 680,000äóñ780,000 years old.  Between 1929 and 1937, 15 partial crania, 11 mandibles, many teeth, some skeletal bones and large numbers of stone tools were discovered in the Lower Cave at Locality 1 of the Peking Man site at Zhoukoudian, near Beijing, in China. Their age is estimated to be between 500,000 and 300,000 years old. Child's skull showing deciduous teeth (baby/primary teeth) and permanent teeth located above. Note the position of the canines in the upper jaw directly under the eye socket (hence the term "eye teeth"). This skull dates from the 19th century and is housed at the Hunterian Collection at the Royal College of Surgeons in London. This was sitting in the back storage space of a friend's shop. Amazing item: it's a tribal door hanger made from a human skull from the Philippines. I'm guessing Ifugao since they liked to raid neighboring villages and deprive people of their heads, and they were also into this kind of hard fiber cord. Placed over the lintel of a door or hut, it conveyed a message about the proprietor. I have to say I own a lot of amazing stuff, but I doubt I'll ever be at a point where I have things like this stored away gathering dust. #skull #humanskull #philippines #tribalart #ifugao #luzon

This is a real human skull that has been carved with a range of occult imagery centered around a depiction of Baphomet!

Baphomet was the idol that the Knights Templar were accused of worshipping during the Inquisition in the early 14th century and has since become a part of multiple pagan, occult and mystical traditions. 
In 1856, Eliphas Levi created the image of a "Sabbatic Goat" that has come to represent Baphomet. The elements of this symbology represent the "sum total of the universe" (including the balance of good and evil). This is a carving by European artist Dolen Carag and the specimen can be shipped worldwide, anywhere the ownership of human osteology is legal. This is a REAL vintage "exploded" human skull! It even features exposed dentition!

This process is often called "exploding" a skull, but is more formally known as a "Beauchene skull" after 18th century french anatomist Claude Beauchene who was renowned for creations such as these, used for medical reference. This is a truly unique specimen.

"Lifelink" Montana spray paint, Montana markers, and liquitex acrylic paint on stretched canvas. The 7th piece to my series "The human virus". It has often been said that bees are responsible for one out of every three bites of food we eat. Most crops grown for their fruits (including vegetables such as squash, cucumber, tomato and eggplant), nuts, seeds, fiber (such as cotton), and hay (alfalfa grown to feed livestock), require pollination by insects. This means that without bees we cannot sustain enough food to feed everyone on this planet meaning the end for most of us. In this painting depicting a human skull and dead bees shows how important bees are to our survival almost like a "lifelink" if they die, we will eventually die as well. I put my all into this piece and I'm very happy with the results. It took time and patience to complete it, but it was all worth it in the end.

Outlines

This unusual piece was purchased at the end of the 19th century and was originally thought to have come from South America when it was cataloged in 1906. It was eventually reattributed to Central Africa, although there is no known tradition to which this instrument may be assigned. Some have suggested that it may have been made for symbolic or clandestine ritual use, but most likely it is a sensational item made by a clever indigenous entrepreneur for trade and profit with Europeans in the 19th century.

Date:19th century
Culture:Central African
Medium:Human skull, wood, antelope horn, skin, gut, hair
Dimensions:5 1/8 í„ 14 3/8 í„ 5 1/2 in. (13 í„ 36.5 í„ 14 cm)
Classification:Chordophone-Lyre-plucked
Credit Line:The Crosby Brown Collection of Musical Instruments, 1889

In honor of today's Day of the Dead celebration I wanted to share a great art piece of a Sugar Skull girl in makeup by @USERNAME_HERE which I captured in Los Angeles recently. Also Andy Warhol had a lifelong interest with death ä_Á especially after his assasination attempt in 1968 by Valerie Solanis. It became a prevailing theme throughout his career as shown in his Skulls silkscreen work from 1976 and his self portrait from the 70s here._ô_Â Notes:
Skulls comprises six canvases, which are displayed together in a vertical grid of three rows of two. Each panel reproduces the same photographic image of a human skull resting on a flat surface and seen from a slightly raised point of view. The black and white photograph on which Skulls is based was taken by Ronnie Cutrone, then one of Warholäó»s assistants. Cutrone positioned the skull on a trestle table, resting it on a piece of plywood covered in white paper in front of a blank studio wall. Warhol instructed him to take several photographs while changing the position of the light source in order to cast a variety of dramatic shadows. According to Vincent Fremont, who worked with Warhol in various roles from 1969, Warhol was very interested in the shapes of these shadows and was delighted with the image used here. The forehead and cheekbone stand out brightly while the eye sockets and other recesses are in deep shadow.

Skulls was made in Warholäó»s New York studio, known as the Factory, on unstretched canvas that had been rolled out flat on the studio floor. Although he had a large number of staff working for him, during the period when this work was made Warhol also employed an assistant named Rupert Smith to help specifically with screen-printing. Synthetic polymer paint, a fast drying alternative to oil paint, was used as the background onto which the image of the skull was screen-printed. The vivacity of the red, yellow, blue, and purple colours used here is at odds with their macabre subject matter. #mexicanholiday #rememberingthedead #lifeanddeath #rememberance #andywarholart #dioslosmuertos

Skull of a baby who died from an extreme case of hydrocephalus, 19th century. Hydrocephalus (from Greek hydro-, meaning "water", and kephalos, meaning "head") is a medical condition in which there is an abnormal accumulation of cerebrospinal fluid in the brain. This causes increased intracranial pressure inside the skull and may cause progressive enlargement of the head if it occurs in childhood, potentially causing convulsion, tunnel vision, and mental disability. It was once informally called äóìwater on the brain,äó and was almost always fatal in earlier periods. With this particular specimen, the skull has opened up like a flower due to the high volume of fluid in the brain. It is currently on display at the University Museum, Utrecht, the Netherlands. Gorgeous photo by Rosamond Purcell for her book Special Cases. #histmed #medicalhistory #medicalhistory #skulls #humanskull #humananatomy #museumobject #anatomy #specimen #hydrocephalus #19thcentury #victorian #darkobject #humanremains

3,300-year-old skull with hair extensions. A team of archeologists lead by Jolanda Bos recently discovered the remains of a woman with an incredibly elaborate hairstyle of lengthy hair extensions in the Egyptian city of Amarna. She was not mummified; her body was simply wrapped in a mat. A selection of 28 skulls from this excavation showed that a variety of hairstyles were worn in Egypt between around 1353-1335 B.C. The heads showed that braids and coils around the ears were popular but often kept short. Fat was a frequently used styling product and Henna was used to hide any stray grey hairs. #archeology #believeitornot #themoreyouknow #hairextensions #fashionguru #ancienthistory #egyptian #humanremains #humanskull #skull #excavation #weaves

Skull, 2200 BC. Although this skull shows four separate holes made by the ancient surgical process of trepanation, there is evidence of regrowth of the bone, indicating that the individual lived on for many years after the operations. In addition to the trepanned holes, we can see evidence of head injury on the top of the skull, supporting the idea that this person had trepanations as a medical treatment following an intracranial trauma.

Also known as trepanation, or trepanning, the process of making a hole through the skull to the surface of the brain might be carried out to treat a range of medical conditions or for more mystical reasons. This would have been done without anesthetic or antiseptics. The skull was excavated from a tomb in Jericho, Israel, in January 1958 and presented to the Wellcome collection, where it is currently in display in London. #histmed #medicalhistorian #medicalhistory #museumobject #skull #humanremains #humanskull #grossanatomy #medschoollife #archeology #excavations #bones

Cemetery attendant arrested with human skulls

A cemetery attendant, Oluwatosin Akorede, has been arrested by Ogun State Police Command for allegedly trading in human parts.

The Command Public Relations Officer, Abimbola Oyeyemi, who made this known to PREMIUM TIMES on Monday, said the suspect was caught with two human skulls.

He said Mr. Akorede was arrested at about 7 p.m. on Sunday at Isale-Oko area of Sagamu in Sagamu Local Government Area of the state following a tip off.

The spokesperson added that police officers led by the Divisional Police Officer, Moses Aduroja, were on routine patrol of the area when the suspect was arrested. äóìThe suspect, who is said to be working in a cemetery situated along Ayepe road Shagamu is currently undergoing interrogation with the view of unravelling the motive behind his action,äó Mr. Oyeyemi said.

He said the Commissioner of Police, Ahmed Iliyasu, has directed that the suspect be transferred to the command headquarters in Eleweran, Abeokuta, for further investigation.
